availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: This manuscript has been described as "the detritus of the Kilbride collection" (Black 2011). It consists of three components, all in Gaelic but distinct in in scribal hand, shape, genre, and subject-matter. These contain religious poetry (Texts 1-13); a fragment of the Ulster Cycle saga, Caithréim Conghail Cláiringhnigh (Text 14); and a contract issued by Duncan MacDougall of Dunollie (1603×1616) (Text 15). All are acephelous and suffer from various other sorts of damage, which is often serious. Nonetheless, at least partial transcriptions of all of these texts have been included in the corpus.

summary.p: NLS Adv. 72.1.31, as currently bound, begins with a collection of poems (Texts 1-13) in Early Modern (or sometimes possibly Middle) Irish. They are either about Colum Cille or attributed to him here or in other manuscripts. The latter type includes dramatic monologues set in the context of his hagiography and general pronouncements on religious themes. There is noticeable overlap in content between this collection and that in Laud Misc. 615, for which see Herbert and Sullivan (1973). Many of the poems are badly affected by erosion or loss of segments of vellum.

Black (2011) has identified the hand that wrote Texts 1-13 as that that wrote 'Aingil Dé dom dín' in BL Egerton 2899 (MS2). Due this latter manuscript having been owned the Campbells of Glen Orchy and due to certain calligraphic, orthographic, and linguistic traits on Hand7's part, he could have been based in such a milieu. The date of Egerton 2899, among other evidence, implies he was working in the 16th century; for more details, see the Introduction.

The fragment (Text 14) of Caithréim Conghail Cláirignigh (edited and translated from another manuscript by MacSweeney (1904)) relates the voyage of the eponymous Ulster king to Lochlann and his return to Ireland via Britain, together with the transactions he undertakes with various kings along the route. The text, which seems to be in conservative Early Modern Irish, follows the prosimetric structure of later Middle Irish narrative, with the prominence voyages to far-flung lands and magic giving a foretaste of later romances. In terms of style, however, it largely avoids the bombastic, adjectival tendences of much later medieval prose narrative. Fol. 6 is in generally good condition but large swathes of fol. 7 appear illegible.

Black (2011) has identified the sole hand responsible for Caithréim Conghail Cláirignigh (Hand27) as that which writes out Beatha Choluim Chille (a version earlier than Ó Domhnaill’s) in Edinburgh, NLS Adv. MS 72.1.40. The latter text’s editor (Grosjean 1928: 112) has suggested that this manuscript version may have been written out in Scotland. That Hand27 is a Scottish scribe is also implied by the fact that he appears in two manuscripts acquired in Scottish contexts, NLS Adv. 72.1.40 having been acquired by the Highland Society of London before 1803.

The MacDougall Contract (Text 15) seems to have been issued by Duncan MacDougall of Dunollie sometime between 1603 and 1616 (Black 1984: 143). Like the rest of the manuscript, it has suffered damage that obscures its details. However, Black has argued from what is left that it concerns a tenant of MacDougall's (also called Duncan), who holds land from him in steelbow and is setting a portion of this land to a sub-tenant. The beginning of the text is lost, and most lines lack their own beginnings and ends, but substantial detail of the agreement is prserved nonetheless. The scribe, Eoghan Mac Pháil (Hand8), flourished 1603×1638

titleStmt.title: A fragment of Caithréim Conghail Cláiringhnigh

physDesc.p: As noted, all three sections of this manuscript are badly damaged, with text lost to erosion and loss of writing surface. Furthermore, Section 1 (fols 1-5) is certainly missing at least some folios (as the end of Text 12 and the beginning of Text 13 is absent). If the Section 2 (fols 6-7) is from a full text of Caithréim Conghail Cláiringhnigh, then its two folios represent a small fraction of the manuscript of which it was originally part. Section 3 (fol. 8), while damaged, probably only ever consisted of a single sheet, as it is a legal document.

Section 1 is laid out in one column per page. The pages are relatively wide and the lines are relatively long, with an an entire quatrain of syllabic verse sometimes fitting on a line. The same anonymous scribe (Hand7) writes out the entirety of the main text.

Section 2 is laid out in the conventional manner for prose, with two columns per page and new sections and embedded verse indicated with capitals. The same anonymous scribe (Hand27) writes out the entirety of the main text.
Section 3 is particularly poorly preserved, but the text seems to have been presented in a single text block, with a signature below. It is in the hand of Eoghan Mac Pháil (Hand8).

supportDesc.support: Section 1 (fols 1-5): Vellum. Section 2 (fols 6-7): Vellum. Section 3 (fol. 8): Paper.
supportDesc.condition: The condition is very poor in places and some text is lost entirely. Away from damaged areas, however, the text can be excellently well-preserved.

summary.p: All three sections became part of the Kilbride collection, where they seem to have been bound together. Before that, beyond the evidence for their origins detailed here, their history is unknown.

langUsage.p: As well as being physically fragmentary, in most cases, Poems 1-13 are written in an unusual and inconsistent orthography, which may repay further examination for dialectal features. Beyond that, however, they appear to be in Early Modern Gaelic with Middle Gaelic influences in places. There are also some sporadic signs of Scottish Gaelic influence on the orthography and sound system. A range of verse styles and forms are represented, including narrative, homiletic exposition, and assertion of ecclesiastical claims via hagiography.

Text 14 is written in relatively conservative, albeit somewhat erratic, orthography. The language is essentially Early Modern, although with relatively more conservative features (accusatives, synthetic verb forms). Stylistically, it includes prose, verse, direct speech, and some detailed descriptions that include some useful specialist vocabulary.

Text 15 is in late Early Modern Gaelic. It is of definite Scottish provenance and relatively practical in nature. Nonetheless, it contains relatively few examples of Scottish Gaelic influence in terms of language, conforming mostly to Early Modern literary norms. The spelling and sound system may be of more interest from this perspective, with Scottish Gaelic features like pre-aspiration potentially attested. The vocabulary of the document is of much interest for its insights into the social and legal history of Gaelic Scotland.

note.p: This reading is extremely tentative. The character being taken here as an "s" in reality looks much more like an "r", which suggests that this might be a form of "comríachtain". That reading is only being rejected because it is inferior in terms of sense.
There is a punctus below the "r", possibly suggesting that it is to be deleted.
The Tironian "et" is faint, as if an attempt has been made to erase it.
There are a number of places in or near Connacht called Baile an tSléibhe; it is not clear which one is referenced here.
There is a mark resembling a Tironian "et" between "conghail" and "cona", but the sentence does not require anything else.
In this instance, "{}" replicates this scribe's style of ceann fo eite; it does not represent an editorial emendation, as elsewhere.

Black (0020336) suggests that this might alternatively be a verbal noun of aingid, producing the meaning "the servant is responsible for defending Donnchadh in night's-portion". However, a verbal noun in this form is not attested elsewhere, so this reading is not being adopted.
Black later proposes a full reading of this sentence (for which, see Slip 0020336), although this is problematic; see previous footnote.
